Module 3, Lesson 2: Collective geoms

In the second lesson of Module 3, you learned about histograms, barplots, and boxplots all of which are collective geoms. Remember that collective geoms are so-called because rather than plotting individual data they plot summaries of the data. A collective geom is intended to show some overall feature of the data instead of specific data points.

Open the R project called Lessons.Rproj and a blank R script. Then, load the necessary packages into the current R session:

library(healthds)
library(tidyverse)

geom_histogram

As you saw in the video, a histogram is created by first binning or grouping together observations having numeric values that are considered near to one another in some sense (more on this in a moment) and then plotting these groups as rectangles with height equal to the number of observations in a bin.

To create a histogram of the infant weights, we use the following code, mapping weight_kg to the x aesthetic:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg), 
                 binwidth = 1)

From the plotted result, we see that two measured weights were between 2.5 and 3.5, because the height of the bar is 2. Similarly, two were between 3.5 and 4.5,3 were between 4.5 and 5.5, and one was between 6.5 and 7.5. By constructing a histogram, we exchange precision of individual measurements (e.g. we cant say anything more than that a measurement feel somewhere between 6.5kg and 7.5kg) for a better characterization of the whole distribution of weight measurements.

This geom has an extra argument that weve not seen before, binwidth, which we set equal to 1 in the call above. Note that it falls outside of the aesthetic mappings in the aes function. This choice means that the size of the bins is equal to 1. For example, the first bin starts at 2.5 and ends at 3.5, hence the width is 3.5 - 2.5 or 1. And the same goes for the rest of the bins: 4.5 - 3.5, 5.5 - 4.5, etc. Different choices of binwidth may give dramatically different results, particularly for small datasets like this one. Try out different values of binwidth to see for yourself.

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg), 
                 binwidth = 0.25)

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg), 
                 binwidth = 2.0)

You might be thinking that only choosing binwidth is not sufficient to determine how the histogram should appear. For example, if binwidth is 1, you could have a bin of (2.5, 3.5) or (2.6, 3.6) or (2.7, 3.7) or How does ggplot choose (2.5, 3.5)? In fact, if you only specify binwidth, by default ggplot will anchor all bins based upon the (potentially theoretical) bin centered at 0, with boundaries equal to half of binwidth in either direction (I say this is potentially theoretical because your numbers may be much much bigger than 0). So this anchoring bin in our case is (-0.5, 0.5). Once you know this bin, all of the other bins become automatically determined, i.e.(0.5, 1.5), (1.5, 2.5), etc.

As you might be figuring out by know, you can override this default behavior by specifying center, as in:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg), 
                 binwidth = 1, 
                 center = 1.5)

Centering the first bin at 1.5, the bins become (2, 3), (3, 4), etc. Alternatively, instead of specifying center, you can specify boundary, which gives the edge of a bin:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg), 
                 binwidth = 1, 
                 boundary = 1)

Setting center = 0.5 gives the same result as boundary = 1 (when binwidth=1).

There are opportunities to have your histogram tell a different story through your choice of binwidth and center or boundary. For example, consider what happens when we move the value of center from 1.5 above to 1.4 below:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg), 
                 binwidth = 1, 
                 center = 1.4)

A small change in one argument results in a much different-looking histogram. Related to this, if you fail to choose binwidth, ggplot will make some default decisions, and these wont necessarily be good decisions:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg))
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Having failed to set binwidth, ggplot informs us of this fact and suggests to choose our own value.

Your responsibility as a data scientist is to choose values that most faithfully represent your data, and this can be challenging sometimes!

Lastly, note that you can create a horizontal histogram by mapping your variable to the y aesthetic:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(y = weight_kg), 
                 binwidth = 1)

Now, the x-axis is used to represent the counts.

Save this script as 03_02collectivegeoms.R.

geom_bar

A barplot, created using geom_bar, is similar to a histogram, the main difference being that it is intended to be used for characters rather than doubles (the Independent Guide for Module 3, Lesson 1 also talks about characters versus doubles). A simple barplot counting the number of observations per infant id is created by:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = id))

Barplots, like histograms, give counts. And from this barplot we see that there are four observations per id.

Often, one wants to incorporate more aesthetics into a barplot. To demonstrate, we will apply some of our dplyr knowledge to add a new variable to our growth_data. Specifically, we will create a variable that equals TRUE when a measured weight exceeds 5kg and FALSE otherwise. Different from the guided practice video, we will create this new variable and assign the resulting data frame to a new dataset called growth_data_expanded (we used this same variable name in Module 2, Lesson 3; although the names are the same, they are unrelated):

growth_data_expanded <- 
  growth_data %>%
  mutate(weight_gt_5kg = weight_kg > 5)

The expression weight_gt_5kg = weight_kg > 5 may be confusing at first glance. Remember from Module 2, Lesson 2 that the = sign is serving as a declaration, and so we are telling R to create a new variable called weight_gt_5kg that takes on value equal to the right-hand side of the equation sign. Focusing now on the right-hand side, weight_kg > 5 is asking a question: is weight_kg greater than 5? And the answer to this question is the value that weight_gt_5kg takes on. This happens on a row-by-row basis, so the answer to the question may be FALSE (no) for one row and TRUE (yes) for another row.

By assigning this expanded dataset to a new object called growth_data_expanded, we preserve this result for future analyses.

Returning to barplots, lets create a barplot that maps this weight_gt_5kg variable to the fill aesthetic:

ggplot(data = growth_data_expanded) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = id, fill = weight_gt_5kg))

Notice how, in contrast to the guided practice, we arent piping the data into ggplot here, but we could:

growth_data_expanded %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = id, fill = weight_gt_5kg))

(remember that the the pipe operator sends the thing that is being piped as the first argument of the function that the pipe points to, which in the case of the function ggplot is data)

We have the same barplot as before but now with each bar filled to represent the number of counts for which weight_gt_5kg is TRUE and FALSE. These colored bars are, by default, stacked on top of each other. We can use the position argument inside of geom_bar change this behavior. For example, to stack the bars next to each other, we do:

ggplot(data = growth_data_expanded) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = id, fill = weight_gt_5kg), 
           position = "dodge")

Each value if the id variable now gets two bars, one for weight_gt_5kg equal to TRUE and another for weight_gt_5kg equal to FALSE. We are abusing the x aesthetic slightly here the fact that the reddish bar corresponding to FALSE is on the left and greenish bar corresponding to TRUE is on the right should not be interpreted to mean that they have different values of id. Dodging the bars this way allows for an easier direct comparison of the colored bars to one another, at the cost of making it slightly more difficult to compare the total counts combining all colors.

We can also normalize the heights of the bars so that the filled bars represent proportions instead of counts:

ggplot(data = growth_data_expanded) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = id, fill = weight_gt_5kg), 
           position = "fill")

(unfortunately, there are two distinct uses of the word fill here. It is an aesthetic that can be mapped inside of the aes() function and also a word, in quotes, that specifies a type of barplot.) Although setting position="fill" doesnt look different at first glance from the default stacked barplot, this is only the case because each value of id has equal numbers of observations. Upon closer inspection one notices that the y-axis ends at 1 instead of at 4 in the stacked barplot. All bars will always have height equal to 1 when using position="fill". Because of this, the default label for the y-axis (count) is no longer accurate, and you can change this label using what you will learn in Module 3, Lesson 3.

One potential source of confusion is understanding the difference between the color and fill aesthetics. Generally speaking, if a geometric object has area to it (like a bar), the fill aesthetic controls the shading of the inside and the color aesthetic controls the shading of its perimeter. If youre not sure which is appropriate, try them both and see which you prefer:

ggplot(data = growth_data_expanded) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = id, color = weight_gt_5kg))

In this case, coloring just the perimeter of the bars makes it hard to visually distinguish between groups, and wed probably prefer to use the fill aesthetic.

Save your script to preserve the additional code youve added to this script.

geom_boxplot

Much of what weve done so far has been within the tidyverse family of packages. In this lesson we briefly leave the tidyverse to learn about some new base R functions: sort and quantile. We also learn about the pull function (which happens to be in the tidyverse although its new to us). We introduce these functions only to help understand how geom_boxplot works.

pull is analogous to select (Module 2, Lesson 3) but with two key differences: it can only include one variable (whereas select can include more than one), and it gives back a vector of numbers rather than a dataset. The advantage to pulling a variable is that we can then use the sort and quantile functions, which both only work on a vector of numbers. Consider the following three lines of code:

growth_data %>% pull(weight_kg)
## [1] 3.0 4.1 4.9 5.5 2.9 4.2 5.5 6.6
growth_data %>% pull(weight_kg) %>% sort()
## [1] 2.9 3.0 4.1 4.2 4.9 5.5 5.5 6.6
growth_data %>% pull(weight_kg) %>% quantile()
##    0%   25%   50%   75%  100% 
## 2.900 3.825 4.550 5.500 6.600

The first pulls the weight_kg variable. From it, you can see the resulting vector. It is still comprised of the measured infant weights, but we have lost all context, e.g.we dont know which id or month each measured weight corresponds to. The second line pulls this variable and then sorts it in increasing order. This should should remind you of the arrange function (but remember that arrange is intended to be used in the context of a dataset, not a vector). The third line pulls this variable and then calculates the minimum, three quartiles, and maximum of this vector.

The first, second, and third quartiles of a set of numbers are those for which 25%, 50%, and 75%, respectively, of the numbers in the set fall below. These quartiles form the box of a boxplot:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
    geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg))

The thick middle line is the second quartile (also called the median), and the left and right edges of the box are the first and third quartiles. From the boxplot, we know that 50% of the measured infant weights fall inside the box. The lines on each end of the boxplot are sometimes called whiskers. As discussed in the videos, the whiskers encompass all data points within 1.5 times the interquartile range (the difference between the third and first quartiles) of the boxs edge.

You dont need to use the quantile function to create a boxplot. All calculations are done automatically simply by calling geom_boxplot.

As with histograms and barplots, you can rotate a boxplot by mapping weight_kg to the y aesthetic:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
    geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(y = weight_kg))

Finally, you can create separate boxplots by mapping a categorical variable, such as id, to another aesthetic, such as y:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
    geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg, y = id))

Save your script once again before closing.
